discussion_comments.comment_body:
> shouldn't the wait return Option<&T> because what if you call wait on SetOnce which isn't initialized.

I think the `SetOnce::wait().await` should only be resolved if any of the following requirements is met:

1. Its value has been initialized.
2. (OR) All other `SetOnce` instances has been dropped but the value is still uninitialized.

I guess you meant that we should return `None` on (2). This should be a reasonable point which I didn't realized before.

Now, there are two options.

```rust
pub async fn wait(&self) -> Option<&T>;

// OR

// Error means all other instances
// has been dropped and value
// is still uninitialized.
pub async fn wait(&self) -> Result<&T, Error>
```

Selecting  `Option<&T>` indicates that we consider it a normal use case that `SetOnce` are never initialized. `Result<&T, Error`> indicates it is not.

What do you think?

